text.tspan: USABILITY OF SINGLE-CELL TRAJECTORY INFERENCE METHODS
Robrecht Cannoodt* ¹ ² ³, Wouter Saelens* ¹ ², Helena Todorov¹ ² ⁴, Yvan Saeys¹ ²

¹ Data mining and Modelling for Biomedicine, VIB Center for Inflammation Research, Ghent, Belgium. ² Department of Applied Mathematics, Computer Science and Statistics, Ghent University, Ghent, Belgium. ³ Center for Medical Genetics, Ghent University Hospital, Ghent, Belgium.

flowRoot.flowPara: Saelens W.*, Cannoodt R.*, Todorov H., Saeys Y. A comparison of single-cell trajectory inference methods. Accepted Jan 2019.
Trajectory inference methods help study dynamic processes by ordering single-cell transcriptomic profiles along a trajectory in an unbiased manner.
Since 2014, at least 71 trajectory inference methods have been developed, but due to high variability in their inputs and outputs, the output of these methods is hard to compare.

In this study, we evaluated a total of 45 methods in terms of cellular ordering, topology, scalability, and usability. Our results highlight the complementarity of existing tools, and that there is no generally best performing method. Instead, the choice of method mostly depends on the dataset characteristics and the trajectory topology present. To assist users in selecting the most appropriate method, we therefore developed a set of guidelines, available as an interactive app at guidelines.dynverse.org.
